I have enough. Now let me write the API.md file (most symbol-intensive). I'll focus strictly on accurate signatures from ports and kernel.  [33m> Write[0m(file_path='/Users/nomind/Code/duh/benchmarks/benchmark-3-docs/worktrees/duh-opus/docs-new/API.md', content='# D.U.H. API Reference\n\nThis reference covers every public class and function exported by\n`duh/kernel/` and `duh/ports/` at commit `645d91a`. Signatures are\ncopied verbatim from the source. Private helpers (names beginning with\n`_`) are omitted.\n\nThe kernel has one overriding rule: **it never imports a concrete\nadapter or a provider SDK.** It depends only on the interfaces in\n`duh.ports`, plus stdlib. Everything the kernel needs from the outside\nworld is injected through a single `Deps` dataclass.\n\n---\n\n## Table of contents\n\n1. [`duh.ports`](#duhports) — abstract protocols\n   - [`duh.ports.approver.ApprovalGate`](#duhportsapproverapprovalgate)\n   - [`duh.ports.context.ContextManager`](#duhportscontextcontextmanager)\n   - [`duh.ports.executor.ToolExecutor`](#duhportsexecutortoolexecutor)\n   - [`duh.ports.memory.MemoryHeader` / `MemoryStore`](#duhportsmemorymemoryheader)\n   - [`duh.ports.provider.ModelProvider`](#duhportsprovidermodelprovider)\n   - [`duh.ports.renderer.Renderer`](#duhportsrendererrenderer)\n   - [`duh.ports.store.SessionStore`](#duhportsstoresessionstore)\n2. [`duh.kernel`](#duhkernel)\n   - [Messages & content blocks](#messages-and-content-blocks)\n   - [Tool protocol](#tool-protocol)\n   - [`Deps`](#deps)\n   - [`Engine` and `EngineConfig`](#engine)\n   - [`query()` — the loop](#query)\n   - [Tokens and cost](#tokens-and-cost)\n   - [Context gate](#contextgate)\n   - [Confirmation tokens](#confirmationminter)\n   - [Taint propagation: `UntrustedStr`](#untrustedstr)\n   - [Attachments](#attachments)\n   - [Audit hook](#audit-hook)\n   - [Auto-memory](#auto-memory)\n   - [Backoff](#backoff)\n   - [Cache tracker](#cachetracker)\n   - [Compact analytics](#compactstats)\n   - [File size guard](#file-size-guard)\n   - [File tracker](#filetracker)\n   - [Git context](#git-context)\n   - [Health check](#healthchecker)\n   - [Job queue](#jobqueue)\n   - [Memory integration](#memory-integration)\n   - [Memory decay](#memory-decay)\n   - [Model capabilities](#model-capabilities)\n   - [Permission cache](#sessionpermissioncache)\n   - [Plan mode](#planmode)\n   - [Post-compact restoration](#post-compact-restoration)\n   - [Query guard](#queryguard)\n   - [Redaction](#redact_secrets)\n   - [Schema validator](#schema-validator)\n   - [Signals / shutdown](#shutdownhandler)\n   - [Skills](#skills)\n   - [Snapshots and ghost mode](#snapshots)\n   - [Tasks](#taskmanager)\n   - [Templates](#templates)\n   - [Tool timeouts](#tool-timeouts)\n   - [Undo stack](#undostack)\n\n---\n\n## `duh.ports`\n\nThe ports package exposes six protocols, re-exported from\n`duh.ports.__init__`:\n\n```python\nfrom duh.ports import (\n    ApprovalGate, ContextManager, MemoryHeader, MemoryStore,\n    ModelProvider, SessionStore, ToolExecutor,\n)\n```\n\nAll of them are `typing.Protocol` subclasses, decorated with\n`@runtime_checkable`, so you can use `isinstance(obj, ModelProvider)`\nfor duck-typed dispatch.\n\n### `duh.ports.approver.ApprovalGate`\n\nChecked before every tool execution by the query loop.\n\n```python\nclass ApprovalGate(Protocol):\n    async def check(\n        self,\n        tool_name: str,\n        input: dict[str, Any],\n    ) -> dict[str, Any]: ...\n```\n\n- **Returns**: `{"allowed": True}` or `{"allowed": False, "reason": "…"}`.\n- **Raises**: implementations should not raise; a denial is signalled\n  through the return value.\n\n**Example**\n\n```python\nclass YesAll:\n    async def check(self, tool_name, input):\n        return {"allowed": True}\n```\n\n### `duh.ports.context.ContextManager`\n\nCompacts messages when the token budget is exceeded.\n\n```python\nclass ContextManager(Protocol):\n    async def compact(\n        self, messages: list[Any], token_limit: int,\n    ) -> list[Any]: ...\n\n    def estimate_tokens(self, messages: list[Any]) -> int: ...\n```\n\n- `compact` returns a **new** list — it must not mutate `messages`.\n\n### `duh.ports.executor.ToolExecutor`\n\nFinds, validates, and runs a tool by name.\n\n```python\nclass ToolExecutor(Protocol):\n    async def run(\n        self,\n        tool_name: str,\n        input: dict[str, Any],\n        *,\n        tool_use_id: str = "",\n        context: Any = None,\n    ) -> str | dict[str, Any]: ...\n```\n\n- Returns the tool\'s output as a string or dict.\n- Raises on tool-not-found or execution errors.\n\n### `duh.ports.memory.MemoryHeader`\n\nImmutable metadata for a single memory topic file.\n\n```python\n@dataclass(frozen=True)\nclass MemoryHeader:\n    filename: str\n    name: str\n    description: str\n    type: str  # "user" | "feedback" | "project" | "reference"\n```\n\n### `duh.ports.memory.MemoryStore`\n\nPersists per-project memory. File-based by convention; stored under\n`~/.config/duh/projects/<sanitized-cwd>/memory/`.\n\n```python\nclass MemoryStore(Protocol):\n    def get_memory_dir(self) -> Path: ...\n    def read_index(self) -> str: ...\n    def write_index(self, content: str) -> None: ...\n    def read_file(self, name: str) -> str: ...\n    def write_file(self, name: str, content: str) -> None: ...\n    def list_files(self) -> list[MemoryHeader]: ...\n    def delete_file(self, name: str) -> None: ...\n```\n\n`write_index` truncates to the last 200 lines. `read_*` return empty\nstring when the target is missing — they never raise.\n\n### `duh.ports.provider.ModelProvider`\n\nThe LLM-facing port. Every provider (Anthropic, OpenAI, Ollama, Gemini,\nGroq, stub) implements this.\n\n```python\nclass ModelProvider(Protocol):\n    async def stream(\n        self,\n        *,\n        messages: list[Any],\n        system_prompt: str | list[str] = "",\n        model: str = "",\n        tools: list[Any] | None = None,\n        thinking: dict[str, Any] | None = None,\n        max_tokens: int | None = None,\n        **kwargs: Any,\n    ) -> AsyncGenerator[dict[str, Any], None]: ...\n```\n\nMust yield events in D.U.H.\'s uniform event schema:\n\n- `{"type": "text_delta", "text": "…"}`\n- `{"type": "thinking_delta", "text": "…"}`\n- `{"type": "tool_use", "id": "…", "name": "…", "input": {…}}`\n- `{"type": "assistant", "message": Message}` — the completed turn\n- `{"type": "error", "error": "…"}`\n\n### `duh.ports.renderer.Renderer`\n\nConsumes engine events, produces terminal output. Three built-in tiers:\n`Bare`, `Rich`, and full TUI.\n\n```python\nclass Renderer(Protocol):\n    def render_text_delta(self, text: str) -> None: ...\n    def render_tool_use(self, name: str, input: dict[str, Any]) -> None: ...\n    def render_tool_result(self, output: str, is_error: bool) -> None: ...\n    def render_thinking(self, text: str) -> None: ...\n    def render_error(self, error: str) -> None: ...\n    def render_permission_request(\n        self, tool_name: str, input: dict[str, Any]\n    ) -> None: ...\n    def finish(self) -> None: ...\n    def handle(self, event: dict[str, Any]) -> None: ...\n```\n\n`handle(event)` is the main dispatcher — it routes an event to the\nappropriate `render_*` method based on `event["type"]`.\n\n### `duh.ports.store.SessionStore`\n\nPersists entire sessions (messages).\n\n```python\nclass SessionStore(Protocol):\n    async def save(self, session_id: str, messages: list[Any]) -> None: ...\n    async def load(self, session_id: str) -> list[Any] | None: ...\n    async def list_sessions(self) -> list[dict[str, Any]]: ...\n    async def delete(self, session_id: str) -> bool: ...\n```\n\n`load` returns `None` when not found. `delete` returns `True` if the\nsession existed.\n\n---\n\n## `duh.kernel`\n\nThe top-level re-exports (`duh.kernel.__init__`):\n\n```python\nfrom duh.kernel import (\n    AssistantMessage, Deps, Engine, Message, Tool, ToolResult,\n    UserMessage, query,\n)\n```\n\n### Messages and content blocks\n\nDefined in `duh.kernel.messages`. All content blocks are frozen\ndataclasses; every block carries a `type` string discriminator.\n\n```python\n@dataclass(frozen=True)\nclass TextBlock:\n    text: str\n    type: str = "text"\n\n@dataclass(frozen=True)\nclass ToolUseBlock:\n    id: str\n    name: str\n    input: dict[str, Any]\n    type: str = "tool_use"\n\n@dataclass(frozen=True)\nclass ToolResultBlock:\n    tool_use_id: str\n    content: str | list[Any]\n    is_error: bool = False\n    type: str = "tool_result"\n\n@dataclass(frozen=True)\nclass ThinkingBlock:\n    thinking: str\n    type: str = "thinking"\n\n@dataclass(frozen=True)\nclass ImageBlock:\n    media_type: str  # image/png, image/jpeg, image/gif, image/webp\n    data: str        # base64-encoded\n    type: str = "image"\n\nContentBlock = (TextBlock | ToolUseBlock | ToolResultBlock\n              | ThinkingBlock | ImageBlock | dict[str, Any])\n```\n\n#### `Message`\n\n```python\n@dataclass\nclass Message:\n    role: str                              # "user" | "assistant" | "system"\n    content: str | list[ContentBlock] = ""\n    id: str                                # uuid4 hex\n    timestamp: str                         # ISO-8601 UTC\n    metadata: dict[str, Any] = field(default_factory=dict)\n```\n\nProperties:\n\n- `text: str` — concatenated text content of all `TextBlock`s.\n- `tool_use_blocks: list[ToolUseBlock | dict]` — every `tool_use`\n  block in `content`.\n- `has_tool_use: bool` — shorthand for `len(tool_use_blocks) > 0`.\n\n#### Constructors\n\n```python\ndef UserMessage(content: str | list[ContentBlock], **kwargs: Any) -> Message\ndef AssistantMessage(content: str | list[ContentBlock], **kwargs: Any) -> Message\ndef SystemMessage(content: str, **kwargs: Any) -> Message\n```\n\n#### Alternation repair\n\n```python\ndef merge_consecutive(messages: list[Message]) -> list[Message]\ndef validate_alternation(messages: list[Message]) -> list[Message]\n```\n\n`merge_consecutive` collapses adjacent same-role messages into one.\n`validate_alternation` additionally inserts synthetic `"continued"`\nmessages wherever alternation breaks, and prepends a synthetic\nuser message when the first one isn\'t user-role. Required by the\nAnthropic API\'s strict alternation rule.\n\n---\n\n### Tool protocol\n\nDefined in `duh.kernel.tool`.\n\n#### Constants\n\n```python\nMAX_TOOL_OUTPUT = 100_000                # 100 KB hard cap\nDEFAULT_TIMEOUT = 120                    # seconds\nTOOL_TIMEOUTS: dict[str, int]            # per-tool overrides\n```\n\n#### `get_tool_timeout`\n\n```python\ndef get_tool_timeout(tool_name: str) -> int\n```\n\nReturns the per-tool timeout, or `DEFAULT_TIMEOUT` if the tool isn\'t\nlisted in `TOOL_TIMEOUTS`.\n\n#### `ToolResult`\n\n```python\n@dataclass\nclass ToolResult:\n    output: str | list[Any] = ""\n    is_error: bool = False\n    metadata: dict[str, Any] = field(default_factory=dict)\n```\n\n#### `ToolContext`\n\nRuntime context passed to every `Tool.call()`.\n\n```python\n@dataclass\nclass ToolContext:\n    cwd: str = "."\n    tool_use_id: str = ""\n    abort_signal: Any = None\n    permissions: Any = None        # ApprovalGate adapter\n    session_id: str = ""\n    metadata: dict[str, Any] = field(default_factory=dict)\n    sandbox_policy: Any = None     # SandboxPolicy | None\n    tool_name: str = ""\n    input_obj: dict[str, Any] = field(default_factory=dict)\n    confirm_token: str | None = None\n    model: str | None = None\n```\n\n#### `Tool`\n\n```python\nclass Tool(Protocol):\n    name: str\n    description: str\n    input_schema: dict[str, Any]\n\n    async def call(\n        self, input: dict[str, Any], context: ToolContext\n    ) -> ToolResult: ...\n\n    @property\n    def is_read_only(self) -> bool: ...      # default False\n\n    @property\n    def is_destructive(self) -> bool: ...    # default False\n\n    async def check_permissions(\n        self, input: dict[str, Any], context: ToolContext\n    ) -> dict[str, Any]: ...                 # default {"allowed": True}\n```\n\nThe only three attributes that must exist are `name`, `description`,\nand `input_schema`; the rest have defaults.\n\n---\n\n### `Deps`\n\n`duh.kernel.deps` — the dependency-injection seam.\n\n```python\n@dataclass\nclass Deps:\n    call_model:    Callable[..., AsyncGenerator[Any, None]] | None = None\n    run_tool:      Callable[..., Awaitable[Any]]            | None = None\n    approve:       Callable[..., Awaitable[dict[str, Any]]] | None = None\n    compact:       Callable[..., Awaitable[Any]]            | None = None\n    hook_registry: Any = None\n    uuid:          Callable[[], str]  # default: uuid4 hex\n    confirm_gate:  Callable[..., Any] | None = None\n    session_id:    str = ""\n    audit_logger:  Any = None\n```\n\n`call_model` and `run_tool` are required for the loop to make progress.\nEverything else is optional and has a graceful fallback.\n\n---\n\n### Engine\n\n`duh.kernel.engine`. Session-level wrapper around `query()`.\n\n#### `EngineConfig`\n\n```python\n@dataclass\nclass EngineConfig:\n    model: str = ""\n    fallback_model: str | None = None\n    max_fallback_retries: int = 1\n    system_prompt: str | list[str] = ""\n    tools: list[Any] = field(default_factory=list)\n    thinking: dict[str, Any] | None = None\n    tool_choice: str | dict[str, Any] | None = None\n    max_turns: int = 1000\n    max_cost: float | None = None\n    cwd: str = "."\n    trifecta_acknowledged: bool = False\n    auto_memory: bool = False\n```\n\n#### `Engine`\n\n```python\nclass Engine:\n    def __init__(\n        self,\n        deps: Deps,\n        config: EngineConfig | None = None,\n        session_store: SessionStore | None = None,\n        structured_logger: "StructuredLogger" | None = None,\n        **kwargs: Any,\n    ): ...\n\n    # read-only properties\n    messages: list[Message]\n    session_id: str\n    turn_count: int\n    total_input_tokens: int\n    total_output_tokens: int\n    model: str\n    cache_tracker: CacheTracker\n    compact_stats: CompactStats\n    max_cost: float | None\n\n    # budgeting\n    def budget_remaining(self, model: str | None = None) -> float | None: ...\n    def estimated_cost(self, model: str | None = None) -> float: ...\n    def cost_summary(self, model: str | None = None) -> str: ...\n\n    # main entry point\n    async def run(\n        self,\n        prompt: str | list[Any],\n        *,\n        max_turns: int | None = None,\n        model: str | None = None,\n    ) -> AsyncGenerator[dict[str, Any], None]: ...\n```\n\nConstruction refuses (via `check_trifecta`) to start a session where\n`READ_PRIVATE | READ_UNTRUSTED | NETWORK_EGRESS` are all present in\nthe tool set without `trifecta_acknowledged=True`.\n\n#### Stream events from `Engine.run`\n\nYields the same event types as [`query`](#query), plus:\n\n- `{"type": "session", "session_id": str, "turn": int}` (first event)\n- `{"type": "context_blocked", "message": str}` — 95 % gate fired\n- `{"type": "budget_warning", …}` — 80 % cost threshold\n- `{"type": "budget_exceeded", …}` — 100 % cost hit, run stops\n- `{"type": "auto_memory", "facts": [...]}` — when `auto_memory=True`\n- `{"type": "usage_delta", "input_tokens": int, "output_tokens": int,\n  "estimated": True, "model": str}` — streaming token estimate\n\n---\n\n### `query`\n\n`duh.kernel.loop.query` — the universal agentic loop.\n\n```python\nasync def query(\n    *,\n    messages: list[Message],\n    system_prompt: str | list[str] = "",\n    deps: Deps,\n    tools: list[Any] | None = None,\n    max_turns: int = 1000,\n    model: str = "",\n    thinking: dict[str, Any] | None = None,\n    tool_choice: str | dict[str, Any] | None = None,\n) -> AsyncGenerator[dict[str, Any], None]\n```\n\nYields the following event types, in approximate order:\n\n| Event                       | Meaning                                    |\n|-----------------------------|--------------------------------------------|\n| `text_delta`                | Streaming model text chunk                 |\n| `thinking_delta`            | Streaming reasoning chunk                  |\n| `content_block_start/stop`  | Low-level block-boundary events (passthrough) |\n| `content_block_delta`       | Low-level streaming delta (passthrough)    |\n| `assistant`                 | Full assistant message (`Message` object)  |\n| `tool_use`                  | `{"id","name","input"}` — tool invocation  |\n| `tool_result`               | `{"tool_use_id","output","is_error"}`     |\n| `tool_result_message`       | Internal — synthetic user message          |\n| `error`                     | `{"error": str}`                          |\n| `done`                      | `{"stop_reason","turns"}` — loop complete  |\n\nConcurrency: read-only tools (those exposing `is_read_only = True`)\nare grouped and run in parallel via `asyncio.gather`; mutating tools\nrun sequentially so on-disk ordering is preserved.\n\nTool result bodies are truncated to `MAX_RESULT_SIZE = 80_000` chars\nbefore being added to the next turn.\n\n---\n\n### Tokens and cost\n\n`duh.kernel.tokens`.\n\n```python\nCHARS_PER_TOKEN: int = 4            # generic conservative default\n\ndef count_tokens(text: str) -> int\ndef count_tokens_for_model(text: str, model: str) -> int\ndef estimate_cost(model: str, input_tokens: int, output_tokens: int) -> float\ndef get_context_limit(model: str) -> int\ndef format_cost(cost: float) -> str\n\nMODEL_CONTEXT_LIMITS: dict[str, int]  # test-patchable override table\n```\n\n- `count_tokens_for_model` uses calibrated chars-per-token ratios per\n  model family: Claude ≈3.5, GPT ≈4.0, local ≈3.5.\n- `get_context_limit` first consults `MODEL_CONTEXT_LIMITS`, then\n  falls back to `duh.kernel.model_caps.get_capabilities(model)\n  .context_window`, then returns the default `100_000`.\n- `format_cost(0.0042)` → `"$0.0042"`; `format_cost(1.234)` → `"$1.23"`.\n- Pricing is in USD per 1 M tokens, hard-coded for popular models and\n  pattern-matched on substrings (`"opus"`, `"haiku"`, `"sonnet"`,\n  `"gpt-4o"`, local model names) for unknowns.\n\n---\n\n### `ContextGate`\n\n`duh.kernel.context_gate`.\n\n```python\nclass ContextGate:\n    BLOCK_THRESHOLD = 0.95\n\n    def __init__(self, context_limit: int): ...\n    def check(self, token_estimate: int) -> tuple[bool, str]: ...\n```\n\nReturns `(True, "")` when the estimate is under 95 % of the context\nwindow, else `(False, reason)` with a human-readable explanation.\nThe engine uses this gate *after* auto-compaction and before any API\ncall.\n\n---\n\n### `ConfirmationMinter`\n\n`duh.kernel.confirmation`. Single-use HMAC-bound tokens for dangerous\ntool calls.\n\n```python\nclass ConfirmationMinter:\n    def __init__(self, session_key: bytes): ...\n    def mint(self, session_id: str, tool: str, input_obj: dict) -> str\n    def validate(\n        self, token: str, session_id: str, tool: str, input_obj: dict\n    ) -> bool\n```\n\nTokens embed `session_id | tool_name | sha256(input) | timestamp`\nand an HMAC signature. `validate` returns `False` for any token older\nthan 300 s, replayed (already seen), or bound to a different\nsession/tool/input.\n\n---\n\n### `UntrustedStr`\n\n`duh.kernel.untrusted`. A `str` subclass that carries a `TaintSource`\ntag through string operations.\n\n```python\nclass TaintSource(str, Enum):\n    USER_INPUT = "user_input"      # untainted\n    MODEL_OUTPUT = "model_output"  # tainted\n    TOOL_OUTPUT = "tool_output"    # tainted\n    FILE_CONTENT = "file_content"  # tainted\n    MCP_OUTPUT = "mcp_output"      # tainted\n    NETWORK = "network"            # tainted\n    SYSTEM = "system"              # untainted\n\nUNTAINTED_SOURCES: frozenset[TaintSource]  # {USER_INPUT, SYSTEM}\n\nclass UntrustedStr(str):\n    def __new__(\n        cls,\n        value: object = "",\n        source: TaintSource = TaintSource.MODEL_OUTPUT,\n    ) -> "UntrustedStr": ...\n\n    source: TaintSource             # property\n    def is_tainted(self) -> bool\n```\n\nEvery str method that returns a `str` is overridden to return an\n`UntrustedStr` carrying the same or merged source: `__add__`,\n`__mod__`, `__mul__`, `format`, `format_map`, `join`, `replace`,\n`strip`, `lstrip`, `rstrip`, `split`, `rsplit`, `splitlines`, `lower`,\n`upper`, `title`, `casefold`, `capitalize`, `swapcase`, `expandtabs`,\n`center`, `ljust`, `rjust`, `zfill`, `translate`, `removeprefix`,\n`removesuffix`, `__getitem__`, and `__format__`.\n\nHelpers:\n\n```python\ndef merge_source(a: Any, b: Any) -> TaintSource\ndef assert_no_tag_loss(value: object, op: str) -> None\n\nclass TaintLossError(RuntimeError): ...\n```\n\nEnvironment variables: `DUH_TAINT_DEBUG=1` logs preserved ops;\n`DUH_TAINT_STRICT=1` raises `TaintLossError` on silent drops.\n\n---\n\n### Attachments\n\n`duh.kernel.attachments`.\n\n```python\nMAX_ATTACHMENT_SIZE = 20 * 1024 * 1024  # 20 MB\n\n@dataclass\nclass Attachment:\n    name: str\n    content_type: str\n    data: bytes\n    metadata: dict[str, Any]\n\n    size: int        # len(self.data)\n    is_image: bool\n    text: str | None\n    base64: str\n\nclass AttachmentManager:\n    def read_file(self, path: str) -> Attachment\n    def detect_content_type(self, filename: str, data: bytes) -> str\n    def to_image_block(self, attachment: Attachment) -> ImageBlock\n    def extract_text(self, attachment: Attachment) -> str\n```\n\n`read_file` raises `FileNotFoundError` on a missing path and\n`ValueError` when the file exceeds `MAX_ATTACHMENT_SIZE`.\n`to_image_block` raises `ValueError` when the attachment isn\'t an\nimage.\n\n---\n\n### Audit hook\n\n`duh.kernel.audit`. PEP 578 bridge: telemetry, not enforcement.\n\n```python\nWATCHED_EVENTS: frozenset[str]  # "open", "socket.connect", "subprocess.Popen", …\n\ndef install(registry: Any) -> None\n```\n\nCall `install(hook_registry)` **once** at process start, after the\n`HookRegistry` exists. The handler is idempotent — second calls\nare a no-op.\n\n---\n\n### Auto-memory\n\n`duh.kernel.auto_memory`.\n\n```python\nasync def extract_memories(\n    messages: list[Message],\n    call_model: CallModelFn,\n    *,\n    model: str = "",\n) -> list[dict[str, str]]\n```\n\nUses the LLM itself to extract up to 3 JSON-formatted key/value facts\nfrom the current conversation. Returns `[]` on any failure; never\nraises.\n\n---\n\n### Backoff\n\n`duh.kernel.backoff`.\n\n```python\ndef is_retryable(exc: BaseException) -> bool\n\nasync def with_backoff(\n    fn: Callable[[], AsyncGenerator[dict[str, Any], None]],\n    *,\n    max_retries: int = 3,\n    base_delay: float = 1.0,\n    max_delay: float = 30.0,\n) -> AsyncGenerator[dict[str, Any], None]\n```\n\nWraps an async-generator factory with exponential backoff + full\njitter. Retries on HTTP 429/503/529 and on the retryable substrings\n`"rate limit"`, `"overloaded"`, `"connection timeout"`, etc.; bails\nimmediately on 400/401/403/404 or auth errors.\n\n---\n\n### `CacheTracker`\n\n`duh.kernel.cache_tracker`.\n\n```python\n@dataclass\nclass CacheTracker:\n    def record_usage(self, usage: dict) -> None\n    def notify_compaction(self) -> None\n    def cache_read_ratio(self) -> float\n    def is_break_detected(self) -> bool\n    def total_cache_read_tokens(self) -> int\n    def total_cache_creation_tokens(self) -> int\n    def summary(self) -> str\n```\n\nRolls a bounded history of `cache_creation_input_tokens` /\n`cache_read_input_tokens` from provider usage metadata. Flags a\n"break" if the read ratio drops by more than 40 % between turns\nwithout a preceding compaction.\n\n---\n\n### `CompactStats`\n\n`duh.kernel.compact_analytics`.\n\n```python\n@dataclass\nclass CompactStats:\n    total_compactions: int = 0\n    total_tokens_freed: int = 0\n    snip_count: int = 0\n    summary_count: int = 0\n    microcompact_count: int = 0\n    dedup_count: int = 0\n\n    def record(self, tier: str, tokens_freed: int) -> None\n    def summary(self) -> str\n```\n\nTiers recognised by `record()`: `"snip"`, `"summary"` (aliased from\n`"summarize"`), `"micro"` / `"microcompact"`, `"dedup"`.\n\n---\n\n### File size guard\n\n`duh.kernel.file_size_guard`.\n\n```python\nMAX_FILE_FRACTION = 0.5\n\n@dataclass(frozen=True)\nclass FileSizeDecision:\n    allowed: bool\n    reason: str\n    estimated_tokens: int\n    budget_tokens: int\n\ndef check_file_size(\n    file_path: str,\n    model: str,\n    *,\n    size_bytes: int | None = None,\n    fraction: float = MAX_FILE_FRACTION,\n) -> FileSizeDecision\n```\n\nRefuses reads estimated to exceed half the model\'s context window. An\n`OSError` during `stat` is treated as "allow" so the real read error\nsurfaces naturally.\n\n---\n\n### `FileTracker`\n\n`duh.kernel.file_tracker`.\n\n```python\n@dataclass(frozen=True)\nclass FileOp:\n    path: str\n    operation: str    # "read" | "write" | "edit"\n    timestamp: datetime\n\nclass FileTracker:\n    ops: list[FileOp]         # property\n\n    def track(self, path: str, operation: str) -> None\n    def clear(self) -> None\n    def summary(self) -> str\n    async def diff_summary(self, *, cwd: str = ".") -> str\n    def diff_summary_sync(self, *, cwd: str = ".") -> str   # deprecated\n```\n\n`diff_summary` shells out to `git diff --stat -- <modified paths>`\nonce, batched, via `asyncio.create_subprocess_exec`. Falls back to a\nplain list when `git` isn\'t available.\n\n---\n\n### Git context\n\n`duh.kernel.git_context`.\n\n```python\ndef get_git_warnings(cwd: str) -> list[str]\ndef get_git_context(cwd: str) -> str | None\n```\n\n`get_git_context` returns a `<git-context>` block suitable for system\nprompt injection (branch, main branch, last 5 commits, short status).\nReturns `None` when `cwd` isn\'t inside a git work tree.\n\n`get_git_warnings` returns strings for detached HEAD, dirty tree, and\nworking on the main branch.\n\n---\n\n### `HealthChecker`\n\n`duh.kernel.health_check`.\n\n```python\nclass HealthChecker:\n    def __init__(self, *, timeout: float = 5.0): ...\n\n    def check_provider(self, provider_name: str) -> ProviderHealth\n    def check_all_providers(self) -> dict[str, ProviderHealth]\n    def check_mcp(\n        self, server_name: str, *, connections: dict[str, Any] | None = None,\n    ) -> MCPHealth\n    def check_all_mcp(\n        self, *,\n        connections: dict[str, Any] | None = None,\n        configs: dict[str, Any] | None = None,\n    ) -> dict[str, MCPHealth]\n```\n\nKnown providers: `"anthropic"`, `"openai"`, `"ollama"`. Returns\n`{"healthy": bool, "latency_ms": int, "error": str | None}`.\n\n---\n\n### `JobQueue`\n\n`duh.kernel.job_queue`.\n\n```python\nclass JobState(str, Enum):\n    pending = "pending"\n    running = "running"\n    completed = "completed"\n    failed = "failed"\n\nMAX_CONCURRENT_JOBS = 5\nMAX_COMPLETED_RETAINED = 50\n\nclass JobQueue:\n    def __init__(\n        self,\n        max_concurrent: int = MAX_CONCURRENT_JOBS,\n        max_completed_retained: int = MAX_COMPLETED_RETAINED,\n    ): ...\n\n    def submit(self, name: str, coro: Coroutine) -> str     # job_id\n    def status(self, job_id: str) -> dict[str, Any]         # KeyError if unknown\n    def results(self, job_id: str) -> str                   # ValueError if still running\n    def list_jobs(self) -> list[dict[str, Any]]             # newest first\n```\n\nJobs transition `pending → running → completed | failed`. Completed\n/ failed jobs are evicted FIFO once more than `max_completed_retained`\nare retained; running / pending jobs are never evicted.\n\n---\n\n### Memory integration\n\n`duh.kernel.memory`.\n\n```python\nMEMORY_TYPES: dict[str, str]   # "user", "feedback", "project", "reference"\n\nFRONTMATTER_TEMPLATE: str\n\ndef make_frontmatter(*, name: str, description: str, type: str) -> str\ndef build_memory_prompt(store: MemoryStore) -> str\n```\n\n`build_memory_prompt` reads `MEMORY.md` and up to the 20 most recent\nfacts via `store.list_facts()` (when available) and returns a\n`<memory>` tag suitable for system prompt injection. Returns `""`\nwhen neither exists.\n\n### Memory decay\n\n`duh.kernel.memory_decay`.\n\n```python\ndef score_facts(\n    facts: list[dict[str, Any]],\n    *,\n    now: datetime | None = None,\n) -> list[tuple[dict[str, Any], float]]\n\ndef gc_memories(\n    store: Any,\n    *,\n    max_facts: int = 200,\n    min_score: float = 0.1,\n    now: datetime | None = None,\n) -> int\n```\n\n`score_facts` returns `(fact, score)` tuples sorted score-descending.\nScore = `0.5 * recency + 0.2 * creation + 0.3 * access_count`. Each\nterm is normalised to [0, 1]. `gc_memories` removes facts below\n`min_score`, then trims to `max_facts` from the tail; returns the\nremoval count.\n\n---\n\n### Model capabilities\n\n`duh.kernel.model_caps`.\n\n```python\n@dataclass(frozen=True)\nclass ModelCapabilities:\n    supports_tools: bool = True\n    supports_thinking: bool = False\n    supports_vision: bool = False\n    supports_cache_control: bool = False\n    max_output_tokens: int = 8192\n    context_window: int = 200_000\n\ndef get_capabilities(model: str) -> ModelCapabilities\ndef model_context_block(model: str) -> str\ndef rebuild_system_prompt(\n    system_prompt: str | list[str], old_model: str, new_model: str,\n) -> str\n```\n\n`model_context_block` builds a `<model-context>` block for the system\nprompt. `rebuild_system_prompt` swaps an existing block when the user\nchanges model via `/model`.\n\n---\n\n### `SessionPermissionCache`\n\n`duh.kernel.permission_cache`.\n\n```python\nclass SessionPermissionCache:\n    def check(self, tool_name: str) -> str | None      # "allow" | "deny" | None\n    def record(self, tool_name: str, decision: str) -> None\n    def clear(self) -> None\n```\n\nDecision vocabulary: `"y"` (one-time allow), `"a"` (always allow),\n`"n"` (one-time deny), `"N"` (never allow). Only `"a"` and `"N"`\npersist in the cache.\n\n---\n\n### `PlanMode`\n\n`duh.kernel.plan_mode`. Two-phase plan-then-execute wrapper around\nan `Engine`.\n\n```python\nclass PlanState(Enum):\n    EMPTY\n    PLANNING\n    PROPOSED\n    EXECUTING\n    DONE\n\n@dataclass\nclass PlanStep:\n    number: int\n    description: str\n    done: bool = False\n\nclass PlanMode:\n    def __init__(self, engine: Engine): ...\n    state: PlanState           # property\n    steps: list[PlanStep]      # property\n    description: str           # property\n\n    def format_plan(self) -> str\n    def clear(self) -> None\n\n    async def plan(self, description: str) -> AsyncGenerator[dict, None]\n    async def execute(self) -> AsyncGenerator[dict, None]\n```\n\n`plan()` forces `tool_choice="none"` during the planning phase so the\nmodel cannot invoke tools while drafting. `execute()` re-enables the\ntool set. Calling `execute()` before `plan()` raises `ValueError`.\n\n---\n\n### Post-compact restoration\n\n`duh.kernel.post_compact`.\n\n```python\nasync def rebuild_post_compact_context(\n    messages: list[Any],\n    file_tracker: Any,\n    max_files: int = 5,\n    max_tokens_per_file: int = 5_000,\n) -> list[Any]\n\ndef restore_plan_context(engine: Any) -> str | None\ndef restore_skill_context(engine: Any) -> str | None\n```\n\nCalled by `Engine._post_compact_rebuild` after any compaction.\n`rebuild_post_compact_context` re-reads the most recently touched\nfiles and appends them as system messages. The two `restore_*`\nhelpers return human-readable context strings the engine folds in.\n\n---\n\n### `QueryGuard`\n\n`duh.kernel.query_guard`. State machine preventing concurrent\n`run()` invocations on the same engine.\n\n```python\nclass QueryState(str, Enum):\n    IDLE = "idle"\n    DISPATCHING = "dispatching"\n    RUNNING = "running"\n\nclass QueryGuard:\n    def __init__(self, *, cancel_on_new: bool = False): ...\n\n    state: QueryState          # property\n    generation: int            # property\n\n    # sync API\n    def reserve(self) -> int\n    def try_start(self, gen: int) -> int | None\n    def end(self, gen: int) -> bool\n    def force_end(self) -> None\n\n    # async API (asyncio.Lock-backed)\n    async def async_reserve(self) -> int\n    async def async_try_start(self, gen: int) -> int | None\n    async def async_end(self, gen: int) -> bool\n    async def async_force_end(self) -> None\n\n    def set_current_task(self, task: asyncio.Task) -> None\n```\n\n`cancel_on_new=True` makes `async_reserve` cancel the in-flight task\ninstead of raising.\n\n---\n\n### `redact_secrets`\n\n`duh.kernel.redact`.\n\n```python\nREDACTED = "[REDACTED]"\n\ndef redact_secrets(text: str) -> str\n```\n\nScrubs PEM private keys, Anthropic/OpenAI/AWS/GitHub API keys, Bearer\ntokens, URL-embedded passwords, and generic\n`SECRET_KEY="…"` assignments. Designed to run on tool output before\nit\'s shown to the model.\n\n---\n\n### Schema validator\n\n`duh.kernel.schema_validator`.\n\n```python\nclass SchemaValidationError(ValueError): ...\n\ndef validate_tool_schema(name: str, schema: dict[str, Any]) -> list[str]\n```\n\nReturns a list of warnings. Raises `SchemaValidationError` only for\nissues that would certainly break the API (non-dict root, missing\n`"type": "object"`). Warnings cover missing property descriptions,\ninvalid types, and `required` entries that don\'t exist.\n\n---\n\n### `ShutdownHandler`\n\n`duh.kernel.signals`.\n\n```python\nDEFAULT_SHUTDOWN_TIMEOUT = 5.0\n\nclass ShutdownHandler:\n    def __init__(self, timeout: float = DEFAULT_SHUTDOWN_TIMEOUT): ...\n\n    shutting_down: bool                    # property\n\n    def trigger(self) -> None\n    def on_shutdown(self, callback: Callable[[], Awaitable[None]]) -> None\n    async def run_cleanup(self) -> None\n    def install(self, loop: asyncio.AbstractEventLoop | None = None) -> None\n```\n\nCleanup callbacks run LIFO under a shared deadline. A second\nSIGINT/SIGTERM forces `sys.exit(1)`; SIGQUIT dumps all thread stacks.\n\n---\n\n### Skills\n\n`duh.kernel.skill`.\n\n```python\n@dataclass\nclass SkillDef:\n    name: str\n    description: str\n    when_to_use: str = ""\n    allowed_tools: list[str] = field(default_factory=list)\n    model: str = ""\n    content: str = ""\n    argument_hint: str = ""\n    source_path: str = ""\n    user_invocable: bool = True\n    context: str = "inline"\n    agent: str = ""\n    effort: str = ""\n    paths: list[str] = field(default_factory=list)\n\n    def render(self, arguments: str = "") -> str\n\ndef load_skills_dir(path: str | Path) -> list[SkillDef]\ndef load_all_skills(cwd: str = ".") -> list[SkillDef]\n```\n\nSkills are markdown files with YAML frontmatter. `load_all_skills`\nsearches four locations in precedence order; the last-loaded wins\nby `name`:\n\n1. `~/.claude/skills/` (Claude Code compat)\n2. `~/.config/duh/skills/`\n3. `<cwd>/.claude/skills/`\n4. `<cwd>/.duh/skills/` (highest priority)\n\nBoth flat (`foo.md`) and directory (`foo/SKILL.md`) layouts are\nsupported. Rendering replaces `$ARGUMENTS` with the user\'s input.\n\n---\n\n### Snapshots\n\n`duh.kernel.snapshot`.\n\n#### Read-only snapshot (legacy)\n\n```python\nclass ReadOnlyExecutor:\n    def __init__(self, inner_run: Callable[..., Awaitable[Any]]): ...\n    async def run(\n        self, tool_name: str, input: dict[str, Any], **kwargs: Any,\n    ) -> Any\n\nclass SnapshotSession:\n    def __init__(self, messages: list[Message]): ...\n\n    messages: list[Message]       # property\n    is_discarded: bool            # property\n\n    def add_message(self, message: Message) -> None\n    def get_new_messages(self) -> list[Message]\n    def discard(self) -> None\n```\n\n`ReadOnlyExecutor` raises `PermissionError` for anything outside\n`READ_TOOLS`. `SnapshotSession` deep-copies the message list at\nfork time.\n\n#### Ghost mode (write overlay)\n\n```python\nGHOST_MAX_FILES = 20\nGHOST_MAX_BYTES = 10 * 1024 * 1024\nGHOST_WARN_TURNS = 40\nGHOST_MAX_TURNS = 50\n\n@dataclass\nclass GhostSnapshot:\n    id: str\n    parent_messages: list[Message]\n    fs_overlay: dict[str, str]\n    created_at: float\n    label: str = ""\n\n    turn_count: int                         # property\n    def increment_turn(self) -> None        # RuntimeError past 50 turns\n    def get_new_messages(self, original_count: int) -> list[Message]\n    def discard(self) -> None\n\nclass GhostExecutor:\n    def __init__(self, real_executor: Any, overlay: dict[str, str]): ...\n\n    async def execute_write(self, path: str, content: str) -> dict[str, Any]\n    async def execute_read(self, path: str) -> dict[str, Any]\n    async def run(\n        self, tool_name: str, input: dict[str, Any], **kwargs: Any,\n    ) -> Any\n    def merge_to_disk(self) -> list[str]\n```\n\n`Write`, `Edit`, `MultiEdit` go into the overlay; `Read` reads overlay\nfirst then real FS; `Bash` is blocked entirely. Overlay caps raise\n`OverflowError` on breach. `merge_to_disk()` flushes the overlay and\nreturns the list of written paths.\n\n---\n\n### `TaskManager`\n\n`duh.kernel.tasks`.\n\n```python\nVALID_STATUSES: set[str] = {"pending", "in_progress", "completed"}\nStatus = Literal["pending", "in_progress", "completed"]\n\n@dataclass\nclass Task:\n    id: str\n    description: str\n    status: Status = "pending"\n    created_at: str\n\nclass TaskManager:\n    def create(self, description: str) -> Task\n    def update(self, task_id: str, status: str) -> Task    # KeyError/ValueError\n    def get(self, task_id: str) -> Task | None\n    def list_all(self) -> list[Task]\n    def summary(self) -> str\n```\n\n`update()` raises `ValueError` for unknown status, `KeyError` for\nunknown task id. In-memory only; no persistence across sessions.\n\n---\n\n### Templates\n\n`duh.kernel.templates`.\n\n```python\n@dataclass\nclass TemplateDef:\n    name: str\n    description: str\n    content: str = ""\n    source_path: str = ""\n\n    def render(self, prompt: str = "") -> str\n\ndef load_templates_dir(path: str | Path) -> list[TemplateDef]\ndef load_all_templates(cwd: str = ".") -> list[TemplateDef]\n```\n\nTemplates replace `$PROMPT` with the caller-supplied prompt.\n`load_all_templates` searches `~/.config/duh/templates/` and\n`<cwd>/.duh/templates/`; the project-local directory wins.\n\n---\n\n### Tool timeouts\n\nAlready listed under the tool protocol. Defaults in seconds:\n\n| Tool       | Timeout |\n|------------|---------|\n| Bash       | 300     |\n| MultiEdit  | 60      |\n| Grep       | 60      |\n| HTTP       | 60      |\n| Read, Write, Edit, Glob, WebFetch, WebSearch, NotebookEdit, Database | 30 |\n| MemoryStore, MemoryRecall | 10 |\n| Task       | 5       |\n| Skill      | 120     |\n\nUnknown tools fall through to `DEFAULT_TIMEOUT = 120` s.\n\n---\n\n### `UndoStack`\n\n`duh.kernel.undo`.\n\n```python\nUndoEntry = tuple[str, str | None]\n\nclass UndoStack:\n    def __init__(\n        self,\n        maxlen: int = 20,\n        *,\n        per_entry_max_bytes: int = 1 * 1024 * 1024,\n        total_max_bytes: int = 8 * 1024 * 1024,\n    ): ...\n\n    depth: int               # property\n    maxlen: int              # property\n    in_memory_bytes: int     # property\n\n    def push(self, file_path: str, original_content: str | None) -> None\n    def undo(self) -> tuple[str, str]             # IndexError if empty\n    def peek(self) -> UndoEntry | None\n    def clear(self) -> None\n```\n\nBounded on two axes: max snapshots (`maxlen`) and max in-memory bytes\n(`total_max_bytes`). When memory is tight, oldest snapshots are\nspilled to `tempfile.mkstemp` files; `undo()` transparently loads\nthem back.\n\n---\n\n## End\n\nThat\'s the public surface of `duh.kernel` and `duh.ports` at\n`645d91a`. Every symbol listed here can be imported from the shown\nmodule path. The [tutorial](TUTORIAL.md) walks through wiring most of\nthem into a working custom-tool session.\n')
