Now the tutorial.  [33m> Write[0m(file_path='/Users/nomind/Code/duh/benchmarks/benchmark-3-docs/worktrees/duh-opus/docs-new/TUTORIAL.md', content='# D.U.H. Tutorial: From Zero to Your First Custom Tool\n\nThis tutorial walks from a fresh clone of D.U.H. (`v0.8.0`, commit\n`645d91a`) to a working custom tool driven by a real `Engine` session.\n\nBy the end you will have:\n\n1. Installed the package in editable mode.\n2. Run a stub-mode session against the built-in tools.\n3. Written a `Tool` that asks for today\'s date, along with its JSON\n   schema and approval policy.\n4. Plugged the tool into a `NativeExecutor`, wired an `Engine`, and\n   driven it with a provider you control.\n\nEvery code block here imports real symbols from the checkout and has\nbeen written against the exact signatures in `duh/kernel/` and\n`duh/ports/`. No invented APIs.\n\n---\n\n## 0. Prerequisites\n\n- Python 3.12 or later (the project sets `requires-python = ">=3.12"`).\n- A POSIX shell. The tutorial shows `bash`; `zsh` works too.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Install\n\nClone and install in editable mode:\n\n```bash\ngit clone https://github.com/nikhilvallishayee/duh.git\ncd duh\npython3 -m venv .venv\nsource .venv/bin/activate\npip install -e .\n```\n\nConfirm the CLI is on your PATH:\n\n```bash\nduh --help | head -n 5\n```\n\nExpected output (first line, the rest depends on local installed\nextras):\n\n```\nusage: duh [-h] [--version] [--print] [--stream-json] [--tui]\n```\n\nInstall the dev extras if you plan to run the test suite:\n\n```bash\npip install -e \'.[dev]\'\npytest -q tests/unit/test_kernel_loop.py\n```\n\nExpected tail (ignore the `=` ruler widths):\n\n```\n...................\nXX passed in Y.Ys\n```\n\nIf the tests pass, your environment is correct.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Your first hello-world against the stub provider\n\nD.U.H. ships with `duh.adapters.stub_provider.StubProvider`, a\ndeterministic provider used for offline testing. It\'s activated by\nsetting `DUH_STUB_PROVIDER=1` — the CLI\'s provider-resolution path\nnotices the env var and skips all real auth/model calls.\n\nRun a one-shot print mode session:\n\n```bash\nDUH_STUB_PROVIDER=1 duh --print "hello"\n```\n\nExpected output (roughly):\n\n```\nstub-ok\n```\n\nYou can override the canned response with `DUH_STUB_RESPONSE`:\n\n```bash\nDUH_STUB_PROVIDER=1 DUH_STUB_RESPONSE="hi world" duh --print "anything"\n```\n\n```\nhi world\n```\n\nTwo things are now true:\n\n1. Your install works end-to-end (argparse → provider resolution →\n   engine → loop → renderer → stdout).\n2. You did not need any real API credentials.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Driving the loop from Python\n\nThe CLI is just one consumer of the kernel. You can also drive it\ndirectly. Create `tutorial_step3.py` in the repo root:\n\n```python\n# tutorial_step3.py\nimport asyncio\nfrom duh.adapters.stub_provider import StubProvider\nfrom duh.kernel import Deps, Engine\nfrom duh.kernel.engine import EngineConfig\n\n\nasync def main() -> None:\n    provider = StubProvider(model="stub-model")\n\n    # Only call_model is strictly required for a text-only session —\n    # run_tool / approve are optional.\n    deps = Deps(call_model=provider.stream)\n\n    engine = Engine(\n        deps=deps,\n        config=EngineConfig(model="stub-model", tools=[]),\n    )\n\n    async for event in engine.run("hello, engine"):\n        print(event.get("type"), "→", event)\n\n\nasyncio.run(main())\n```\n\nRun it:\n\n```bash\npython tutorial_step3.py\n```\n\nExpected output (one event per line; omit irrelevant noise — exact\nordering matches this):\n\n```\nsession → {\'type\': \'session\', \'session_id\': \'...\', \'turn\': 1}\ntext_delta → {\'type\': \'text_delta\', \'text\': \'stub-ok\'}\nusage_delta → {\'type\': \'usage_delta\', \'input_tokens\': ..., \'output_tokens\': 1, \'estimated\': True, \'model\': \'stub-model\'}\nassistant → {\'type\': \'assistant\', \'message\': Message(role=\'assistant\', ...)}\ndone → {\'type\': \'done\', \'stop_reason\': \'end_turn\', \'turns\': 1}\n```\n\nThe `usage_delta` event might not appear on short responses (it only\nfires every 40 streamed chars). The `session` event is always first;\n`done` is always last. The sequence you see is the canonical D.U.H.\nevent stream.\n\nRead carefully: `engine.run` is an `async def` that returns an\n`AsyncGenerator[dict[str, Any], None]`. Consumers iterate with\n`async for`. Every event is a plain dict — no hidden objects, no\nprovider-specific fields.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Understanding the `Tool` contract\n\nBefore writing a tool, look at the protocol. Open\n`duh/kernel/tool.py`:\n\n```python\nclass Tool(Protocol):\n    name: str\n    description: str\n    input_schema: dict[str, Any]\n\n    async def call(\n        self, input: dict[str, Any], context: ToolContext\n    ) -> ToolResult: ...\n```\n\nThat\'s it. Optional extras are two properties (`is_read_only`,\n`is_destructive`) and one async method (`check_permissions`). No base\nclass to inherit from, no metaclass magic. If your object walks like\na `Tool`, the kernel accepts it.\n\nTwo supporting dataclasses you\'ll use:\n\n```python\n@dataclass\nclass ToolResult:\n    output: str | list[Any] = ""\n    is_error: bool = False\n    metadata: dict[str, Any] = field(default_factory=dict)\n\n@dataclass\nclass ToolContext:\n    cwd: str = "."\n    tool_use_id: str = ""\n    # ... (see API.md for the full list)\n    session_id: str = ""\n    model: str | None = None\n```\n\nReturn a `ToolResult`. The kernel translates it to a `ToolResultBlock`\nunder the hood (see `duh.kernel.loop._execute_block`). If\n`is_error=True` the loop surfaces it as an error to the model; the\nconversation continues, it does not halt.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Writing the tool\n\nOur tutorial tool returns the current date. It demonstrates:\n\n- A correct JSON schema (validated by\n  `duh.kernel.schema_validator.validate_tool_schema`).\n- A capability declaration (for the trifecta check).\n- `is_read_only = True` so the loop can dispatch it concurrently\n  with other read-only tools.\n- A simple `check_permissions` override that denies future dates.\n\nCreate `tutorial_step5.py`:\n\n```python\n# tutorial_step5.py\nfrom datetime import datetime, timezone\nfrom typing import Any\n\nfrom duh.kernel.tool import ToolContext, ToolResult\nfrom duh.security.trifecta import Capability\n\n\nclass TodayTool:\n    """Return today\'s date in the user\'s chosen format."""\n\n    name = "Today"\n    description = "Return today\'s UTC date. Optional format like \'iso\' or \'ymd\'."\n    capabilities = Capability.NONE\n\n    input_schema: dict[str, Any] = {\n        "type": "object",\n        "properties": {\n            "format": {\n                "type": "string",\n                "description": "Either \'iso\' (ISO-8601) or \'ymd\' (YYYY-MM-DD). Default: iso.",\n                "enum": ["iso", "ymd"],\n            },\n        },\n        "required": [],\n    }\n\n    @property\n    def is_read_only(self) -> bool:\n        return True\n\n    @property\n    def is_destructive(self) -> bool:\n        return False\n\n    async def check_permissions(\n        self, input: dict[str, Any], context: ToolContext\n    ) -> dict[str, Any]:\n        # The model should never ask about the future.\n        if "future" in str(input).lower():\n            return {"allowed": False, "reason": "No future queries."}\n        return {"allowed": True}\n\n    async def call(\n        self, input: dict[str, Any], context: ToolContext\n    ) -> ToolResult:\n        now = datetime.now(timezone.utc)\n        fmt = input.get("format", "iso")\n        if fmt == "ymd":\n            output = now.strftime("%Y-%m-%d")\n        else:\n            output = now.isoformat()\n        return ToolResult(output=output)\n```\n\n### Validate the schema\n\nBefore you wire the tool in, make sure its schema is well-formed.\n`validate_tool_schema` returns a list of warnings and raises\n`SchemaValidationError` for fatal problems:\n\n```python\n# tutorial_step5_validate.py\nfrom duh.kernel.schema_validator import validate_tool_schema\nfrom tutorial_step5 import TodayTool\n\ntool = TodayTool()\nwarnings = validate_tool_schema(tool.name, tool.input_schema)\nprint(f"Warnings for {tool.name}: {warnings}")\n```\n\nRun it:\n\n```bash\npython tutorial_step5_validate.py\n```\n\nExpected output:\n\n```\nWarnings for Today: []\n```\n\nAn empty list means the schema is perfectly clean. Try breaking the\nschema — set `"type": "array"` at the root — and you\'ll see\n`SchemaValidationError: Tool \'Today\': input_schema root must have\n"type": "object", got "type": \'array\'`.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Wiring the tool into a `NativeExecutor`\n\n`NativeExecutor` is the adapter the CLI uses by default. It\nimplements `duh.ports.executor.ToolExecutor`: given a tool name and\na dict of args, look up the tool, build a `ToolContext`, enforce\nper-tool timeouts (`duh.kernel.tool.get_tool_timeout`), and call\n`tool.call(...)`.\n\nRegister `TodayTool` with it and drive it directly:\n\n```python\n# tutorial_step6.py\nimport asyncio\nfrom duh.adapters.native_executor import NativeExecutor\nfrom tutorial_step5 import TodayTool\n\n\nasync def main() -> None:\n    executor = NativeExecutor()\n    executor.register(TodayTool())\n\n    print("Tools registered:", executor.tool_names)\n\n    out = await executor.run("Today", {"format": "ymd"})\n    print("Result:", out)\n\n\nasyncio.run(main())\n```\n\nRun it:\n\n```bash\npython tutorial_step6.py\n```\n\nExpected output (date will match today\'s):\n\n```\nTools registered: [\'Today\']\nResult: 2025-04-24\n```\n\nIf the tool isn\'t found, `NativeExecutor.run` raises `KeyError("Tool\nnot found: Today")`. If `check_permissions` denies, it raises\n`PermissionError`. Both propagate up through the loop as error\nevents.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Setting an approval policy\n\nOutside the tutorial, the CLI picks an `ApprovalGate` from\n`--approval-mode`. There are four built-in adapters in\n`duh.adapters.approvers`:\n\n- `AutoApprover` — allows everything. Safe only in a sandbox.\n- `InteractiveApprover` — prompts the user per call\n  (`y` / `a` / `n` / `N`), optionally backed by a\n  `SessionPermissionCache`.\n- `RuleApprover` — deny by tool name, by command substring, or by\n  path prefix.\n- `TieredApprover` — the 3-tier model (`SUGGEST` / `AUTO_EDIT` /\n  `FULL_AUTO`), with a hard-coded git-safety check that blocks\n  `git push --force`, `git reset --hard`, `git clean -f`, and\n  `git branch -D` across *every* tier.\n\nFor the tutorial we\'ll compose a `RuleApprover`:\n\n```python\n# tutorial_step7.py\nimport asyncio\nfrom duh.adapters.approvers import RuleApprover\n\n\nasync def main() -> None:\n    approver = RuleApprover(denied_tools={"Bash"})\n\n    # Today is fine\n    print(await approver.check("Today", {"format": "iso"}))\n\n    # Bash is denied\n    print(await approver.check("Bash", {"command": "ls"}))\n\n\nasyncio.run(main())\n```\n\nRun it:\n\n```bash\npython tutorial_step7.py\n```\n\nExpected output:\n\n```\n{\'allowed\': True}\n{\'allowed\': False, \'reason\': "Tool \'Bash\' is denied by policy"}\n```\n\nThe `check` coroutine is exactly the signature the kernel expects:\n`deps.approve(tool_name, tool_input) -> dict[str, Any]`. If\n`allowed` is falsy, the loop emits a `tool_result` with\n`is_error=True` and `"Tool use denied: <reason>"` as content. The\nconversation continues — the model sees the denial and can adjust.\n\n---\n\n## 8. End-to-end: engine + stub provider + custom tool\n\nThe stub provider never actually emits a `tool_use` event, so to\nobserve the full path we\'ll use a tiny hand-rolled provider that\n*does*. This simulates what Anthropic / OpenAI would return — it\'s\nstill inside D.U.H.\'s uniform event schema, so nothing in the kernel\nknows the difference.\n\n```python\n# tutorial_step8.py\nimport asyncio\nfrom typing import Any, AsyncGenerator\n\nfrom duh.adapters.approvers import RuleApprover\nfrom duh.adapters.native_executor import NativeExecutor\nfrom duh.kernel import Deps, Engine\nfrom duh.kernel.engine import EngineConfig\nfrom duh.kernel.messages import Message\n\nfrom tutorial_step5 import TodayTool\n\n\nclass ScriptedProvider:\n    """A provider that yields a canned tool-use on the first turn,\n    then a final text response on the second turn.\n    """\n\n    def __init__(self) -> None:\n        self._turn = 0\n\n    async def stream(\n        self, *, messages, system_prompt="", model="", tools=None,\n        thinking=None, max_tokens=None, tool_choice=None, **kwargs,\n    ) -> AsyncGenerator[dict[str, Any], None]:\n        self._turn += 1\n        if self._turn == 1:\n            # Turn 1: ask the engine to run TodayTool.\n            tool_use = {\n                "type": "tool_use",\n                "id": "tool_use_1",\n                "name": "Today",\n                "input": {"format": "ymd"},\n            }\n            yield {\n                "type": "assistant",\n                "message": Message(\n                    role="assistant",\n                    content=[tool_use],\n                    metadata={"stop_reason": "tool_use"},\n                ),\n            }\n        else:\n            # Turn 2: we have seen the tool_result; give a final answer.\n            text = "The date came back. Done."\n            yield {"type": "text_delta", "text": text}\n            yield {\n                "type": "assistant",\n                "message": Message(\n                    role="assistant",\n                    content=[{"type": "text", "text": text}],\n                    metadata={"stop_reason": "end_turn"},\n                ),\n            }\n            yield {"type": "done", "stop_reason": "end_turn", "turns": 2}\n\n\nasync def main() -> None:\n    executor = NativeExecutor()\n    executor.register(TodayTool())\n\n    approver = RuleApprover()  # default: allow everything\n    provider = ScriptedProvider()\n\n    deps = Deps(\n        call_model=provider.stream,\n        run_tool=executor.run,\n        approve=approver.check,\n    )\n    engine = Engine(\n        deps=deps,\n        config=EngineConfig(\n            model="scripted-model",\n            tools=[TodayTool()],   # so the loop knows Today is read-only\n        ),\n    )\n\n    async for event in engine.run("what\'s today\'s date?"):\n        kind = event.get("type")\n        if kind == "tool_use":\n            print(f"TOOL_USE  {event[\'name\']} {event[\'input\']}")\n        elif kind == "tool_result":\n            print(f"TOOL_RESULT  {event[\'output\']}  is_error={event[\'is_error\']}")\n        elif kind == "text_delta":\n            print(f"TEXT      {event[\'text\']}")\n        elif kind == "done":\n            print(f"DONE      stop={event[\'stop_reason\']}  turns={event[\'turns\']}")\n\n\nasyncio.run(main())\n```\n\nRun it:\n\n```bash\npython tutorial_step8.py\n```\n\nExpected output (the exact date will differ):\n\n```\nTOOL_USE  Today {\'format\': \'ymd\'}\nTOOL_RESULT  2025-04-24  is_error=False\nTEXT      The date came back. Done.\nDONE      stop=end_turn  turns=2\n```\n\nWhat just happened:\n\n1. `Engine.run` appended your prompt as a `UserMessage`, fired\n   `SETUP` + `TASK_CREATED` hooks (nothing listening, so they no-op),\n   and called `query(...)`.\n2. `query` called `ScriptedProvider.stream` and saw an `assistant`\n   event whose content carried a `tool_use` block.\n3. Because `TodayTool.is_read_only == True`, the loop batched it\n   into the concurrent group and dispatched\n   `deps.run_tool("Today", {"format": "ymd"})`. The\n   `RuleApprover.check` allowed it.\n4. The `tool_result` event was emitted. A synthetic user message\n   carrying the result was appended to the messages list and\n   `tool_result_message` was yielded (but the engine swallowed it).\n5. `query` called the provider again. This time we returned a text\n   response, which the engine captured and streamed out.\n6. `done` terminated the turn. The engine recorded per-turn token\n   estimates, emitted any budget events (none, because\n   `max_cost` was unset), and wrote the session if a\n   `SessionStore` were configured (none here).\n\nYou\'ve now seen every part of the architecture: ports (`Deps`),\nadapters (`NativeExecutor`, `RuleApprover`, your `ScriptedProvider`),\nkernel (`Engine`, `query`, `Tool`, `Message`), events, and\nstreaming.\n\n---\n\n## 9. Optional: wiring a real slash command\n\nSlash commands live in `duh.cli.slash_commands.SlashDispatcher`. To\nteach the REPL a new command, add an entry to the `_HANDLERS` dict\nand matching help in `SLASH_COMMANDS`. Example (for reference — don\'t\nactually patch the CLI from your tutorial dir; this is how you\'d\ncontribute one):\n\n```python\n# in duh/cli/slash_commands.py — illustrative only\nclass SlashDispatcher:\n    def _handle_date(self, arg: str) -> tuple[bool, str]:\n        from datetime import datetime, timezone\n        sys.stdout.write(f"  {datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat()}\\n")\n        return True, self.ctx.model\n\nSlashDispatcher._HANDLERS["/date"] = SlashDispatcher._handle_date\nSLASH_COMMANDS["/date"] = "Print the current UTC date."\n```\n\nThe handler contract is `(self, arg: str) -> tuple[bool, str]`. The\nfirst element is `should_continue`; the second is either the new\nactive model or a sentinel string recognised by the REPL\n(`"\\x00compact\\x00"`, `"\\x00snapshot\\x00<arg>"`,\n`"\\x00plan\\x00<arg>"`). A regression test in\n`tests/unit/test_registry_unified.py` keeps `_HANDLERS` and\n`SLASH_COMMANDS` in sync — if you add one, add both.\n\n---\n\n## 10. Exploring further\n\nYou\'ve now seen every piece you need to build against D.U.H.\nprogrammatically. Useful next steps, each grounded in a specific\nsymbol in the checkout:\n\n- **Ask the engine to save sessions.** Implement\n  `duh.ports.store.SessionStore` and pass it to `Engine(...,\n  session_store=my_store)`. The engine calls `save(session_id,\n  messages)` at the end of every turn and never raises on a failure;\n  it logs a warning. `duh.adapters.file_store.FileSessionStore` is\n  the reference impl.\n- **Add compaction.** Pass `deps.compact = my_fn`, where\n  `my_fn(messages, token_limit) -> list[Message]`. When total\n  estimated tokens cross 80 % of the context window (per\n  `duh.kernel.tokens.get_context_limit`), the engine calls it\n  automatically. See `duh.adapters.compact.AdaptiveCompactor` for\n  the built-in.\n- **Track files.** `NativeExecutor` already owns a\n  `duh.kernel.file_tracker.FileTracker` that records every\n  `Read`/`Write`/`Edit`. `await executor.file_tracker.diff_summary()`\n  shows `git diff --stat` across exactly those paths.\n- **Handle undo.** The same executor owns a\n  `duh.kernel.undo.UndoStack`. `executor.undo_stack.undo()` restores\n  the last mutation.\n- **Plan before acting.** Wrap your `Engine` in\n  `duh.kernel.plan_mode.PlanMode(engine)` and call `plan("do X")`,\n  review `plan_mode.steps`, then `execute()`.\n- **Use attachments.** `AttachmentManager().read_file("docs/pic.png")`\n  returns an `Attachment`; `.to_image_block(att)` yields an\n  `ImageBlock` you can stuff into a user message.\n- **Strict taint mode.** Set `DUH_TAINT_STRICT=1` in the env and any\n  silent taint drop (e.g. a str op that returns plain `str`) will\n  raise `duh.kernel.untrusted.TaintLossError`. Useful when\n  refactoring tool implementations.\n- **Inspect the audit event stream.** Call\n  `duh.kernel.audit.install(hook_registry)` once at process start.\n  Every `PEP 578` event in `WATCHED_EVENTS` will be forwarded as\n  `HookEvent.AUDIT` to your registry.\n\nYou now know how to extend D.U.H. without touching the kernel. The\n[ARCHITECTURE](ARCHITECTURE.md) doc has the big picture; the\n[API](API.md) reference has the exact signatures for anything you\nwant to import. Happy hacking.\n')
